\( \Rightarrow t_n = A + B(2n-1) \\ \Rightarrow t_n = (A+B) + (n-1)(2B) \)

So, \( a = A+B\, , \, d = 2B \)

quest_title: Two batteries of emf 1V and 4V and internal resistances 1\(\Omega\) and 2\(\Omega\) are connected in parallel. Find their equivalent emf.

\(I=I_{1}+I_{2}\)
\(I=\cfrac{E_{1}}{R_{1}}+\cfrac{E_{2}}{R_{2}}\)
\(I=\cfrac{1}{1}+\cfrac{4}{2}\)
\(\therefore I=3 \mathrm{A}\)
Further,
\(r=\cfrac{r_{1} r_{2}}{r_{1}+r_{2}}\)
\(r=\cfrac{1 \times 2}{1+2}\)
\(\therefore r=\cfrac{2}{3} \Omega \)
\( \therefore E=I r\)
\(\quad E=3 \times \cfrac{2}{3} \)
\( \therefore E=2 \mathrm{V}\)

quest_title: "Heat cannot by itself flow from a body at lower temperature to a body at higher temperature" is a statement or consequence of
explanation_txt:
Second law of thermodynamics states that the entropy of the universe always increases.

In classical thermodynamics, entropy is defined \(S=\cfrac{dQ}{T}\)

In a process, let's say transfer of heat (dQ) takes place from system A to system B. Suppose the temperature of system A is \(T_{A}\) and the temperature of system B is \(T_{B}\).

System which receives heat i.e. system B has its entropy increased whereas system A which loses its heat has its entropy decreased.

Net Entropy change in universe due to transfer of heat \(dQ\),

\(\Delta S=-\cfrac{dQ}{T_{A}}+\cfrac{dQ}{T_{B}}\)

\(\Delta S=dQ\left(\cfrac{1}{T_{B}}-\cfrac{1}{T_{A}}\right)\)

From second law of thermodynamics, \(\Delta S \ge 0\).

For this to happen, \(T_{A}>T_{B}\).

Therefore, heat transfer only takes place from body at higher temperature to body at lower temperature.
